354":"1354","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1418":"1418","1 April 1660":"1 April 1660","Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Berkeley, Gloucestershire, England":"Berkeley, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Boulton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Bolton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bolton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places in northern England named Bolton (Lancashire, Northumberland, Westmorland, and Yorkshire) or from Boulton in Derbyshire and East Lothian in Scotland, from Old English <i>bothl</i> ‘dwelling, house’ (see   Bold   1) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."]}]},{"name":"Margarett","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretha","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margarethe","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":95,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margarett Boulton was born about 1360, in Hampshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Richard Faulkner about 1383, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1360–":"umbes 1360–Surnud","1354–Male":"1354–Surnud","1394–1418":"1394–1418","–1458":"–1458","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","Abt 1383":"umbes 1383","1458":"1458","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1455":"1455","1354":"1354","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1418":"1418","1 April 1660":"1. aprill 1660","Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Berkshire, 